msgid "Querying with Wildcards"
msgstr ""

msgid "In addition to using other Linux commands, the rpm command supports some search options. You can pass a wildcard to <command>rpm –qa</command> (but not just <command>rpm –q</command>, you need the <literal>–a</literal> to look for all packages). For example:"
msgstr ""

msgid "<command>rpm -qa \"kernel*\"</command>"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"kernel-2.6.33.6-147.fc13.x86_64\n"
"kernel-2.6.33.5-112.fc13.x86_64\n"
"kernel-devel-2.6.33.5-112.fc13.x86_64\n"
"kernel-headers-2.6.33.6-147.fc13.x86_64\n"
"kernel-2.6.33.5-124.fc13.x86_64\n"
"kernel-devel-2.6.33.5-124.fc13.x86_64\n"
"kernel-devel-2.6.33.6-147.fc13.x86_64"
msgstr ""

msgid "The quotation marks around \"kernel*\" are to prevent the Linux shell from expanding the wildcard character, *, to try to match a list of file names in the local directory. By passing the command-line parameter as \"kernel*\", the rpm program gets to see the * character. Otherwise, the shell expands the parameter and the program, rpm in this case, never sees the *."
msgstr ""

msgid "This command searches for all package names starting with send. You can reverse this with an exclamation mark. For example:"
msgstr ""

msgid "$ rpm -qa '!send*'"
msgstr ""

msgid "This command works sort of like <command>grep –v</command> and searches for all packages that do not start with \"send\"."
msgstr ""

msgid "There are quite a few other Linux commands you can use in pipelines with the <command>rpm –qa</command> command to better filter and display the data, such as <command>wc –l</command> to count the number of packages that you query. You can also use a number of other query options to find out more specialized information from the RPM database."
msgstr ""

msgid "Finding which packages own files"
msgstr ""

msgid "One of the common problems with package management comes when you want to track a given file on your system back to the package that “owns” the file (that is, the package that, when installed, installed the particular file)."
msgstr ""

msgid "The <option>-qf</option> option tells the rpm command to query for all packages that own a particular file. You can also use the longer option, <option>--file</option>, in place of <option>–f</option>. The basic syntax follows:"
msgstr ""

msgid "<command>rpm -qf <replaceable>filename</replaceable></command>"
msgstr ""

msgid "For example, the grep command used in previous examples is really a file. (Just about all Linux commands are a file of some sort, be it a shell script or an executable application.) You can use a few Linux commands to determine which package provides this handy program."
msgstr ""

msgid "First, we need the exact path to the file. For Linux commands, you can use the <command>which</command> command, if the program is in your path. (The grep program must be in your path, or commands with grep will fail.)"
msgstr ""

msgid "Try the following command:"
msgstr ""

msgid "<command>which grep</command>"
msgstr ""

msgid "This command returns the path to grep:"
msgstr ""

msgid "/bin/grep"
msgstr ""

msgid "We can now check which package owns this file with the following command:"
msgstr ""

msgid "<command>rpm -qf /bin/grep</command>"
msgstr ""

msgid "grep-2.6.3-1"
msgstr ""

msgid "You can also use the Linux back-tick operator to perform this check with one command."
msgstr ""

msgid "<command>rpm -qf `which grep`</command>"
msgstr ""

msgid "If you use the bash shell, you can use the $(command parameters) syntax in place of the back tick, or `, characters. For example:"
msgstr ""

msgid "<command>rpm -qf $(which grep)</command>"
msgstr ""

msgid "If no package owns a given file, you’ll see output like the following:"
msgstr ""

msgid "<command>rpm -qf mail</command>"
msgstr ""

msgid "file mail is not owned by any package"
msgstr ""

msgid "Often, the package that owns a file does not have an intuitive name. The ssh command, for example, is owned by the openssh-clients package, as shown following:"
msgstr ""

msgid "<command>rpm -qf `which ssh`</command>"
msgstr ""

msgid "openssh-clients-5.4p1-3"
msgstr ""

msgid "As you can see, the name of a command does not always correspond directly to the name of the package that provides that command. This is where the <command>rpm –qf</command> command proves very useful. Otherwise, you would just have to know that OpenSSH is the project responsible for this command."
msgstr ""

msgid "Symbolic Links"
msgstr ""

msgid "The <command>rpm -qf</command> command follows symbolic links. This was not always true with older versions of RPM, but modern RPM versions can trace package ownership to files placed in linked directories."
msgstr ""

msgid "For example, the directory /usr/lib/X11 is a link to the real directory, /usr/X11R6/lib/X11. You can track the package ownership of a file in that directory, XKeysymDB, for example, by using the following command:"
msgstr ""

msgid "<command>rpm -qf /usr/lib/X11/XKeysymDB</command>"
msgstr ""

msgid "XFree86-4.2.0-72"
msgstr ""

msgid "This file, XKeysymDB, really resides in /usr/X11R6/lib/X11."
msgstr ""

